d}}\n\n== Certifications and sales ==\n{{Wikipedia books|The Way We Were (Barbra Streisand album)}}\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Australia|type=album|artist=Barbra Streisand|title=The Way We Were|award=Gold|relyear=1974|certyear=2000|access-date=January 15, 2017 |refname=\"Australia certification\"}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Canada|type=album|artist=Barbra Streisand|title=The Way We Were|award=Platinum|relyear=1974|certyear=1978|access-date=January 15, 2017 |refname=\"Canada certification\"}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=album|region=Japan ([[Recording Industry Association of Japan|RIAJ]])|artist=Barbra Streisand|title=The Way We Were|nocert=true|salesamount=4,000|salesref=<ref name=\"Oricon\" />}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=album|artist=Barbra Streisand|title=The Way We Were|award=Silver|relyear=1974|certyear=1976|access-date=January 15, 2017 |refname=\"United Kingdom certification\"}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=album|artist=Barbra Streisand|title=The Way We Were|award=Platinum|number=2|relyear=1974|certyear=1998|access-date=January 15, 2017 |refname=\"United States certification\"}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Works cited\n*{{cite book|last1=Bly|first1=Bellie|title=Barbra Streisand: The Untold Story|date=September 1, 1994|publisher=Pinnacle|ref=harv|isbn=0-7860-0051-1|url=https://archive.org/details/barbrastreisandu00blyn}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Dietz|first1=Dan|title=Off Broadway Musicals, 1910\u20132007: Casts, Credits, Songs, Critical Reception and Performance Data of More Than 1,800 Shows |date=March 9, 2010 |publisher= McFarland |ref=harv|isbn= 0-7864-5731-7 }}\n*{{cite book|last1=Eberwein|first1=Robert|title=Armed Forces: Masculinity and Sexuality in the American War Film |date=June 13, 2007 |publisher= Rutgers University Press |ref=harv|isbn= 0-8135-4150-6 }}\n*{{cite book|last1=Jordan|first1=Herb|title=Motown in Love: Lyrics from the Golden Era|date=2006|publisher=Pantheon |ref=harv|isbn= 0-375-42200-5 }}\n*{{cite book|last1=Meier|first1=Levi|title=Jewish Values in Psychotherapy: Essays on Vital Issues on the Search for Meaning |date=1988|publisher=University Press of America |ref=harv|isbn= 0-8191-6928-5 |edition= illustrated }}\n*{{cite book|last1=Okamoto|first1=Satoshi|title=Oricon Album Chart Book: Complete Edition 1970\u20132005|date=2006|publisher=[[Oricon|Oricon Entertainment]] |ref=harv|isbn= 4-87131-077-9 }}\n*{{cite book|last1=Perone|first1=James E.|title=The Sound of Stevie Wonder: His Words and Music|date=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|ref=harv|isbn=0-275-98723-X|edition=illustrated, annotated|url=https://archive.org/details/soundofsteviewon00pero}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Pohly|first1=Linda|title=The Barbra Streisand Companion: A Guide to Her Vocal Style and Repertoire|date=January 1, 2000|publisher=Greenwood Press|ref=harv|isbn=0-313-30414-9|edition=illustrated|url=https://archive.org/details/barbrastreisandc00lind}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Waldman|first1=Allison J.|title=The Barbra Streisand Scrapbook|date=2001|publisher=Citadel Press|ref=harv|isbn= 0-8065-2218-6 |edition= illustrated, revised}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Discogs master|74490|The Way We Were|type=album}}\n\n{{Barbra Streisand}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Way We Were, The}}\n[[Category:1974 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums arranged by Marty Paich]]\n[[Category:Albums arranged by Peter Matz]]\n[[Category:Albums arranged by Claus Ogerman]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Tommy LiPuma]]\n[[Category:Barbra Streisand albums]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at United Western Recorders]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Way We Were\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Barbra Streisand]]\n| cover      = Barbra Streisand \u2013 The Way We Were.jpg\n| alt        = Barbra Streisand appears wearing a black shawl around her head with her hand against a wall.\n| released   = {{Start date|1974|01|01|mf=y}}\n| recorded   = 1969\u20131973\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[United Western Recorders|United-Western Recorders]]<br /> <small>([[Los Angeles]])</small>\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Contemporary pop]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=35|s=13}}\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Wally Gold]]|[[Tommy LiPuma]]|[[Marty Paich]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Barbra Streisand...and Other Musical Instruments]]\n| prev_year  = 1973\n| next_title = [[The Way We Were: Original Soundtrack Recording]]\n| next_year  = 1974\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The Way We Were\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[The Way We Were (song)|The Way We Were]]\n | single1date = {{Start date|1973|09|27|mf=y}}\n | single2     = [[All in Love Is Fair#Barbra Streisand version|All in Love Is Fair]]\n | single2date = {{Start date|1974|03}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''The Way We Were''''' is the fifteenth studio album recorded by American vocalist [[Barbra Streisand]]. It was released on January 1, 1974 by [[Columbia Records]]. The record was compiled immediately following the commercial success of [[lead single]] \"[[The Way We Were (song)|The Way We Were]]\". Six of the tracks on the album was meant for the singer's unreleased 1970 project ''The Singer''. Following the distribution of the soundtrack for the [[The Way We Were|1973 film of the same name]], Columbia added a caption to Streisand's LP (''Featuring the Hit Single The Way We Were and All in Love Is Fair'') in order to minimize confusion between the two albums.\n\nCovering a wide array of themes and topics, Streisand sings about recovering relationships, social awareness, and love in general. Like the majority of Streisand's catalog, ''The Way We Were'' was described as a [[Pop music|contemporary pop]] album blended with her signature vocal style. In terms of production, she heavily worked with [[Tommy LiPuma]] and [[Wally Gold]], while [[Marty Paich]] contributed to the title track. \n\nThe lead single (\"[[The Way We Were (song)|The Way We Were]]\") was released on September 27, 1973 and became a chart topper in both the United States and Canada. It was also [[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1974|the top-selling single in the former country in 1974]]. The second and final single, \"[[All in Love Is Fair#Barbra Streisand version|All in Love Is Fair]]\", was released in March 1974 and also charted in the two aforementioned countries.\n\nThe album received generally favorable reviews from [[Music journalism|music critics]], who praised Streisand's vocals and found the record capable of being extremely successful. However, some critics felt the album was not carefully planned out and Streisand was acting out the tracks rather than actually singing them. Commercially, ''The Way We Were'' topped the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] in the United States and reached the top ten on album charts in Australia and Canada. It also entered the charts in Japan and the United Kingdom. Due to strong sales, it has since been certified 2\u00d7 Platinum in the United States by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).\n\n== Background and release ==\nThe concept for the record first developed in late 1973, following the success of \"[[The Way We Were (song)|The Way We Were]]\", which was written specifically for the [[The Way We Were|1973 film of the same name]] starring Streisand and [[Robert Redford]].<ref name=\"Movie release date\" /> American composer and producer [[Marvin Hamlisch]] was commissioned to write the melody for the track, which he found to be hugely challenging due to Streisand's wants. She had wanted him to produce the composition in [[Key (music)|minor key]], but he instead wrote it in major key due to his fear that the song's lyrics would be revealed too quickly to the listener.<ref name=\"The Super Seventies review\">{{cite news|title=\"The Way We Were\" \u2013 Barbra Streisand: Columbia 45944|url=http://www.superseventies.com/1974_1singles.html|accessdate=November 14, 2016|publisher=[[MTV Classic (U.S. TV network)|The Super Seventies]]|date=February 1, 1974|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804014356/http://www.superseventies.com/1974_1singles.html|archivedate=August 4, 2016}}</ref> According to the liner notes of her 1991 [[greatest hits album]] ''[[Just for the Record (Barbra Streisand album)|Just for the Record]]'', \"The Way We Were\", \"All in Love is Fair\", \"Being at War with Each Other\", and \"Something So Right\" were the only tracks specifically recorded and created for the album.<ref name=\"Just for the Record\">{{cite AV media notes |title=[[Just for the Record (Barbra Streisand album)|Just for the Record]] |others=Barbra Streisand |year=1991 |type=Liner notes |publisher=Columbia |id=CK 48648 }}</ref> The majority of the project's material consisted of demos and recordings from Streisand's recording sessions with [[Alan and Marilyn Bergman|Alan Bergman]] and [[Alan and Marilyn Bergman|Marilyn Bergman]] for an unreleased album titled ''The Singer''.<ref name=\"allmusicreview\" /> Both \"The Best Thing You've Ever Done\" and \"Summer Me, Winter Me\" were previously released together as a non-album single by Streisand in April 1970, and were originally intended for inclusion on the [[The Owl and the Pussycat (album)|official soundtrack]] to her 1970 film ''[[The Owl and the Pussycat (film)|The Owl and the Pussycat]]''.<ref name=\"United States TBTUED single\">{{cite AV media notes |title=''\"The Best Thing You've Ever Done\" / \"Summer Me, Winter Me\"'' |others=Barbra Streisand |year=1970 |type=Liner notes |publisher=Columbia |id=4-45147}}</ref>\n\nRecording sessions for the album took place at [[United Western Recorders|United-Western Recorders]] in [[Los Angeles]] between September 1969 and December 1973, while the mixing was performed at Hollywood Sound during that same time period. \"What Are You Doing the Rest of Your Life?\" and \"My Buddy\"/\"How About Me\" were the first two songs recorded, while \"Being at War with Each Other\", \"Something So Right\", and \"All in Love Is Fair\" were the final three to be completed. [[Al Schmitt]] handled the [[Audio engineer|engineering]] and [[Mixing console|mixing]] aspects for the finished tracks, while [[Doug Sax]] mastered the pieces at The Mastering Lab, also in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"The Way We Were liner notes\" /> Streisand and [[Columbia Records]] released ''The Way We Were'' on January 1, 1974 as her fifteenth studio album overall, and first since 1973's ''[[Barbra Streisand\u2026and Other Musical Instruments]]''.<ref name=\"The Way We Were single certification\" /><ref name=\"Barbra Streisand\u2026and Other Musical Instruments\">{{cite AV media notes |title=[[Barbra Streisand\u2026and Other Musical Instruments]] |others=Barbra Streisand |year=1973 |type=Liner notes |publisher=Columbia |id=PC 32655}}</ref> However, Columbia switched the title of the album at the last minute to ''Featuring the Hit Single The Way We Were and All in Love Is Fair'' in order to distinguish Streisand's record from the 1974 soundtrack of the same name with the same release date.<ref name=\"allmusicreview\" /> The same label issued this version as an [[8-track tape|8-track cartridge]] in 1974, with a differing track listing: both \"Something So Right\" and \"Summer Me, Winter Me\" are broken into two separate parts increasing the amount of tracks on the record from ten to twelve.<ref name=\"The Way We Were 2 liner notes\" /> The album was later released in the CD and digital formats on February 5, 2008.<ref name=\"Amazon CD\">{{cite web|title=The Way We Were: Barbra Streisand|url=https://www.amazon.com/Way-We-Were-Barbra-Streisand/dp/B0012GMVU8|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=January 16, 2017|date=February 5, 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118033436/https://www.amazon.com/Way-We-Were-Barbra-Streisand/dp/B0012GMVU8|archivedate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n[[File:Paul Simon 25-07-2008 1.jpg|left|thumb|240px|alt=Paul Simon sings live with a guitar in hand.|Streisand recorded [[Paul Simon]]'s \"Something So Right\" for ''The Way We Were''.]]\nAs a whole, the record is a [[Pop music|contemporary pop]] piece, incorporating elements from Streisand's signature musical style.<ref name=\"The Barbra Streisand Scrapbook\" /> ''The Way We Were'' begins with \"Being at War with Each Other\", a cover of the [[Carole King]] song from her 1973 studio album, ''[[Fantasy (Carole King album)|Fantasy]]'', although King wrote the track specifically for Streisand.<ref name=\"Fantasy Carole King\">{{cite AV media notes |title=[[Fantasy (Carole King album)|Fantasy]] |others=[[Carole King]] |year=1973 |type=Liner notes |publisher=[[Epic Records|Epic]] |id=EK-34962 }}</ref> Produced by LiPuma, she sings about various topics, ranging from socialization and relationships.<ref name=\"The Barbra Streisand Companion\">{{harvnb|Pohly|2000|p=74}}</ref> She also claims that all humans stem from \"one father\" and \"one mother\" and how differing opinions only \"complicate our lives\".<ref name=\"Jewish Values in Psychotherapy\">{{harvnb|Meier|1988|p=81}}</ref> \"[[Something So Right (song)|Something So Right]]\" is also a cover and originally the [[A-side and B-side|B-side]] track to [[Paul Simon]]'s 1973 single \"[[Take Me to the Mardi Gras]]\".<ref name=\"Something So Right Paul Simon\">{{cite AV media notes |title=''\"[[Something So Right (song)|Something So Right]]\"'' |others=[[Paul Simon]] |year=1973 |type=Liner notes |publisher=[[CBS Records International|CBS]] |id=CBS 1578 }}</ref> It focuses heavily on the songwriting rather than the production, although the composition was the second included to be produced by LiPuma.<ref name=\"The Barbra Streisand Companion 2\">{{harvnb|Pohly|2000|p=97}}</ref> \"The Best Thing You've Ever Done\" was originally written in 1970 by Charnin who maintained interest in creating a composition for Streisand.<ref name=\"United States TBTUED single\" /> Additionally, [[Wally Gold]] handled the production for the track, the first of six on the album.<ref name=\"The Way We Were liner notes\" /> Lead single \"The Way We Were\" is the album's fourth track. In particular, its lyrics detail the personal life of Katie Morosky, the character Streisand portrays in the previously mentioned film, and her troubling relationship with boyfriend Hubbell Gardiner.<ref name=\"Marvin Hamlisch death\">{{cite news|last1=Corliss|first1=Richard|title=Remembrance: Nobody Did It Better: Memories of Marvin Hamlisch, 1944\u20132012|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2012/08/07/nobody-did-it-better-memories-of-marvin-hamlisch-1944-2012/|accessdate=November 14, 2016|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=August 7, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127152011/http://entertainment.time.com/2012/08/07/nobody-did-it-better-memories-of-marvin-hamlisch-1944-2012/|archivedate=November 27, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"The Huffington Post lyrics\">{{cite news|last1=Grad|first1=Laurie Burrows|title=Memories: Misty Water-Colored Memories Of The Way We Were|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/laurie-burrows-grad/loss-of-spouse_b_9582238.html|accessdate=November 27, 2016|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=April 8, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127152703/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/laurie-burrows-grad/loss-of-spouse_b_9582238.html|archivedate=November 27, 2016}}</ref> Track five, \"All in Love Is Fair\", is a [[Stevie Wonder]] cover but is fronted by Streisand's own personal take on it.<ref name=\"The Barbra Streisand Scrapbook\">{{harvnb|Waldman|2001|p=54}}</ref> She sings about a failing relationship through the use of clich\u00e9s and obvious messages regarding love.<ref name=\"The Sound of Stevie Wonder\">{{harvnb|Perone|2006|p=53}}</ref><ref name=\"Motown in Love\">{{harvnb|Jordan|2006|p=2}}</ref>\n\n\"What Are You Doing the Rest of Your Life?\" was written by French composer [[Michel Legrand]] (who would continue writing songs with Streisand for years) and Alan and Marilyn Bergman. Gold also produced it, while [[Peter Matz]] arranged the instruments and orchestration that accompanied the composition.<ref name=\"The Way We Were liner notes\" /> Seventh and eighth tracks \"Summer Me, Winter Me\" and \"Pieces of Dreams\", respectively, also feature contributions from Legrand, with the former originally created specifically for ''The Singer'' and the latter a cover of the 1970 version for the film ''[[Pieces of Dreams (film)|Pieces of Dreams]]''.<ref name=\"Barbra Streisand: The Untold Story\">{{harvnb|Bly|1994|p=243}}</ref><ref name=\"Pieces of Dreams song\">{{cite web|last1=LoBianco|first1=Lorraine|title=Pieces of Dreams|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/455928%7C456002/Pieces-of-Dreams.html|publisher=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|accessdate=January 16, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118103556/http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/455928%7C456002/Pieces-of-Dreams.html|archivedate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> \"I've Never Been a Woman Before\" is song written by Tom Baird and [[Ron Miller (songwriter)|Ron Miller]] for ''Cherry'', an unproduced musical based on the [[William Inge]] play ''[[Bus Stop (play)|Bus Stop]]''.<ref name=\"Off Broadway Musicals\">{{harvnb|Dietz|2010|p=84}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://castalbums.org/recordings/Cherry-1972-Demo-Recording/10930/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-03-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320145357/http://castalbums.org/recordings/Cherry-1972-Demo-Recording/10930/ |archivedate=2017-03-20 }}</ref> The closing song on the record is a medley of \"[[My Buddy (song)|My Buddy]]\" and \"[[How About Me?|How About Me]]\", from [[Gus Kahn]], [[Walter Donaldson]], and [[Irving Berlin]].<ref name=\"The Way We Were liner notes\" /> The first part of the melody details someone affected by the loss of a friend, particularly a soldier who died during combat, as noted by author Robert Eberwein in his 2007 book ''Armed Forces; Masculinity and Sexuality in the American War Film''.<ref name=\"Armed Forces\">{{harvnb|Eberwein|2007|p=27}}</ref>\n\n== Singles ==\n[[File:Marvin Hamlisch - Oscars (cropped).jpg|right|thumb|180px|alt=The song's lead songwriter appears holding two awards for his credited work in the single.|Hamlisch was awarded two [[Academy Awards]] for his credited work on \"The Way We Were\".]]\nThe album's lead single \"The Way We Were\" was released as a [[Gramophone record|7\" record]] on September 27, 1973, roughly three weeks before the premiere of the accompanying film.<ref name=\"Movie release date\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/way_we_were/ |title=The Way We Were (1973) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=January 15, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118034648/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/way_we_were/ |archivedate=January 18, 2017 }}</ref> The song was largely successful after its initial release, where it reached number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and spent twenty-three consecutive weeks among the ranking.<ref name=\"Billboard February 2, 1974\">{{cite web|title=The Hot 100 \u2013 The Week Of February 2, 1974|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1974-02-02|work=Billboard|accessdate=November 14, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227213037/http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1974-02-02|archivedate=December 27, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Billboard April 27, 1974\">{{cite web|title=The Hot 100 \u2013 The Week Of April 27, 1974|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1974-04-27|work=Billboard|accessdate=November 14, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228193844/http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1974-04-27|archivedate=December 28, 2016}}</ref> Its success was replicated in Canada, where it was also number one.<ref name=\"Canada single peak\">{{cite web|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 4966a|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4966a&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4966a.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4966a|publisher=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]. [[Library and Archives Canada]]|accessdate=January 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118120223/http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4966a&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4966a.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4966a|archivedate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> \"The Way We Were\" was additionally the top-selling single in the United States in 1974 according to the list compiled by ''Billboard''.<ref name=\"Year End\">{{cite web|url=http://longboredsurfer.com/charts/1974|title=Top 100 Hits for 1974|work=Billboard|accessdate=November 14, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107045525/http://longboredsurfer.com/charts/1974|archivedate=November 7, 2016}}</ref> It was also sent to [[Adult contemporary music|adult contemporary radio]], where it topped the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary charts]] in both the United States and Canada.<ref name=\"United States AC peak\">{{cite web|title=Barbra Streisand \u2013 Chart history|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/280667/Barbra+Streisand/chart?f=341|publisher=[[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Billboard Adult Contemporary]] for Barbra Streisand|accessdate=January 15, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Canada AC peak\">{{cite web|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 5008|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.5008&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.5008.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.5008|publisher=RPM. Library and Archives Canada|accessdate=January 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006104319/http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.5008&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.5008.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.5008|archivedate=October 6, 2016}}</ref> On August 19, 1997, \"The Way We Were\" was certified platinum by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]], signifying sales of over 1,000,000 copies.<ref name=\"The Way We Were single certification\">{{cite web|title=American certifications \u2013 Barbra Streisand |url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=Barbra+Streisand&ti=The+Way+We+Were#search_section|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=January 15, 2017}}</ref> The single has since been considered to be one of her [[signature song]]s.<ref name=\"Signature song\">{{cite web|last1=Passafiume|first1=Andrea|title=Trivia & Fun Facts About The Way We Were|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/467350%7C0/The-Way-We-Were.html|publisher=Turner Classic Movies|accessdate=November 23, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127085352/http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/467350%7C0/The-Way-We-Were.html|archivedate=November 27, 2016}}</ref> For their work on the track, Hamlisch and the Bergman's won the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] at the [[46th Academy Awards]], with Hamlisch also winning the [[Academy Award for Best Original Score]] for his work on the film.<ref name=\"Oscars1974\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1974|title=The 46th Academy Awards (1974) Nominees and Winners|accessdate=December 31, 2011|date=1974|publisher=[[Academy Awards]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402003953/http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1974|archivedate=April 2, 2015}}</ref> It additionally won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]] in 1974 and the [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year]] in 1975.<ref name=\"Golden Globe\">{{cite web|title=Winners & Nominees Best Original Song \u2013 Motion Picture|url=http://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/best-original-song-motion-picture|publisher=[[Hollywood Foreign Press Association]]|accessdate=December 31, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106035845/http://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/best-original-song-motion-picture|archivedate=January 6, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Grammy award\">{{cite web|title=17th Annual Grammy Awards|url=https://www.grammy.com/awards/17th-annual-grammy-awards|publisher=[[The Recording Academy]]|accessdate=December 31, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170101161440/https://www.grammy.com/awards/17th-annual-grammy-awards|archivedate=January 1, 2017}}</ref> On the [[National Endowment for the Arts]] and [[Recording Industry Association of America]]'s list of the top 365 \"Songs of the Century\", \"The Way We Were\" was placed at number 298.<ref name=\"Songs of the century\">{{cite news|title=Songs of the Century|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Music/03/07/list.top.365.songs/index.html|accessdate=November 17, 2016|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=March 7, 2001|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502005739/http://edition.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Music/03/07/list.top.365.songs/index.html|archivedate=May 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\n\"All in Love Is Fair\" was released as the album's second single in March 1974,<ref name=\"United States AiLIF single\">{{cite AV media notes |title=''\"All in Love Is Fair\" / \"[[My Buddy (song)|My Buddy]]\"/\"[[How About Me?|How About Me]]\"'' |others=Barbra Streisand |year=1974 |type=Liner notes |publisher=[[Columbia Records|Columbia]] |id=4-46024}}</ref> a cover of the Stevie Wonder original for his 1973 album, ''[[Innervisions]]''.<ref name=\"Innervisions\">{{cite AV media notes |title=[[Innervisions]] |others=[[Stevie Wonder]] |year=1973 |type=Liner notes |publisher=[[Motown|Tamla]] |id=T 326L}}</ref> Columbia also released it as a 7\" single paired alongside the medley of \"My Buddy\" and \"How About Me\".<ref name=\"United States AiLIF single\" /> Matthew Greenwald from [[AllMusic]] was so fond of her rendition that he wrote: \"It is no doubt one of the most graceful and memorable hooks from the era, and Streisand's performance \u2013 particularly her phrasing of this line \u2013 is unforgettable\".<ref name=\"AllMusic Streisand review\">{{cite web|last1=Greenwald|first1=Matthew|title=Barbra Streisand \u2013 ''All in Love Is Fair''|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/all-in-love-is-fair-mt0036284278|accessdate=January 16, 2017|website=AllMusic|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110091858/http://www.allmusic.com/song/all-in-love-is-fair-mt0036284278|archivedate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> It failed to replicate the success of \"The Way We Were\", but it managed to peak at numbers 63 and 60 in the United States and Canada, respectively.<ref name=\"Billboard April 20, 1974\">{{cite web|title=The Hot 100 \u2013 The Week Of April 20, 1974|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1974-04-20|work=Billboard|accessdate=January 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110114755/http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1974-04-20|archivedate=January 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Canada AiLIF\">{{cite web|title=Top RPM Singles: Issue 5024b|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.5024b&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.5024b.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.5024b|publisher=RPM. Library and Archives Canada|accessdate=January 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118120645/http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.5024b&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.5024b.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.5024b|archivedate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> It additionally reached the top ten of the Adult Contemporary chart, also compiled by ''Billboard''.<ref name=\"United States AC peak\" />\n\nIn 1972, Streisand's version of \"What Are You Doing the Rest of Your Life?\" was released as a [[Promotional recording#Promo single|promotional single]] in the United States in the 7\" vinyl format. It was paired alongside \"The Best Thing You've Ever Done\", which is also included on ''The Way We Were''.<ref name=\"United States WAYDtRoYL single\">{{cite AV media notes |title=''\"[[What Are You Doing the Rest of Your Life?]]\" / \"The Best Thing You've Ever Done\"'' |others=Barbra Streisand |year=1972 |type=Liner notes |publisher=Columbia |id=13-33207}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"allmusicreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-way-we-were-mw0000650840|title=Barbra Streisand \u2013 ''The Way We Were''|website=[[AllMusic]]|last1=Ruhlmann|first1=William|accessdate=January 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126065634/http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-way-we-were-mw0000650840|archivedate=January 26, 2017}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n|rev2Score = B\u2013<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=089919026X|chapter=Consumer Guide '70s: S|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_chap.php?k=S&bk=70|accessdate=March 13, 2019|via=robertchristgau.com}}</ref>\n}}\n''The Way We Were'' has received generally favorable reviews from music critics. [[Robert Christgau]] enjoyed the overall sound of the album, noting that the catchiness of roughly half the album allows for the songs to be replayed over and over.<ref name=\"CG\" /> The editors at ''Billboard'' were appreciative of the release, and singled out ''The Way We Were'' in its \"Spotlight\" section for the February 9, 1974 issue. The publication highlighted album tracks \"Being at War with Each Other\" and \"All in Love Is Fair\" and declared: \"This is the way Streisand should sound.\"<ref name=\"Billboard review\">{{cite journal|title=Billboard's Top Album Picks|journal=Billboard|date=February 9, 1974|volume=86|issue=6|page=61|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1ycEAAAAMBAJ|accessdate=January 9, 2017|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> Stephen Holden from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' labeled it \"her best album in years\"; he also found that her voice sounds just \"as fresh as it did in the sixties\".<ref name=\"Super Seventies reviews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.superseventies.com/spstreisandbarbra.html|title=''The Way We Were'' \u2013 Barbra Streisand|publisher=The Super Seventies|accessdate=January 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923154835/http://www.superseventies.com/spstreisandbarbra.html|archivedate=September 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nJon Landau, also from ''Rolling Stone'', was disappointed by the singer's effort, writing that she \"no longer sings songs\", but rather \"acts them out\". He referenced her catalogue and stated: \"I've enjoyed Barbra Streisand's music in the past, but of the 20 albums I listened to<!--not a mistake--> to write this column, ''The Way We Were'' was not only the most disappointing, but the most difficult to get all the way through.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone review 1\">{{cite news|last1=Landau|first1=Jon|title=Barbra Streisand: The Way We Were|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/barbrastreisand/albums/album/118213/review/6067409/the_way_we_were|accessdate=January 15, 2017|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=June 6, 1974|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609052227/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/barbrastreisand/albums/album/118213/review/6067409/the_way_we_were|archivedate=June 9, 2008}}</ref> AllMusic's William Ruhlmann awarded the album three out of five stars but found it obvious that the record was \"thrown together\" instead of being orchestrated and thought out carefully. He also declared that the success of the title track \"propelled th[e] album to the top of the charts\".<ref name=\"allmusicreview\" />\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nIn the United States, the album debuted at number 97 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart for the week ending February 16, 1974,<ref name=\"Billboard 200 February 16, 1974\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/1974-02-16 |title=Billboard 200: The Week Of February 16, 1974 |work=Billboard |accessdate=July 1, 2016 |date=February 16, 1974 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118211925/http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/1974-02-16 |archivedate=January 18, 2017 }}</ref> and by February 26, had already sold 500,000 copies and was certified Gold.<ref name=\"United States certification\" /> The following week it rose to number 39,<ref name=\"Billboard 200 February 23, 1974\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/1974-02-23 |title=Billboard 200: The Week Of February 23, 1974 |work=Billboard |accessdate=July 1, 2016 |date=February 23, 1974 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118212136/http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/1974-02-23 |archivedate=January 18, 2017 }}</ref> and on March 16 of the same year, it reached the top position.<ref name=\"Billboard 200 March 16, 1974\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/1974-03-16 |title=Billboard 200: The Week Of March 16, 1974 |work=Billboard |accessdate=July 1, 2016 |date=March 16, 1974 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826214239/http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/1974-03-16 |archivedate=August 26, 2016 }}</ref> It became Streisand's second number one and seventh top five album, with the other number-one being ''[[People (Barbra Streisand album)|People]]'' (1964).<ref name=\"United States\" /> ''The Way We Were'' spent two weeks at the highest position before falling to number four on March 30.<ref name=\"Billboard 200 March 23, 1974\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/1974-03-23 |title=Billboard 200: The Week Of March 23, 1974 |work=Billboard |accessdate=July 1, 2016 |date=March 23, 1974 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118212103/http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/1974-03-23 |archivedate=January 18, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"Billboard 200 March 30, 1974\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/1974-03-30 |title=Billboard 200: The Week Of March 30, 1974 |work=Billboard |accessdate=July 1, 2016 |date=March 30, 1974 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118211734/http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/1974-03-30 |archivedate=January 18, 2017 }}</ref> It continued dropping on the charts but managed to stay within the top 10 of the list for a total of six weeks.<ref name=\"Billboard 200 April 13, 1974\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/1974-04-13 |title=Billboard 200: The Week Of April 13, 1974 |work=Billboard |accessdate=July 1, 2016 |date=April 13, 1974 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118211550/http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/1974-04-13 |archivedate=January 18, 2017 }}</ref> The Recording Industry Association of America changed its certification status to Platinum for shipments upwards of 1,000,000 sales, and again on September 23, 1998, ''The Way We Were'' was certified for selling over 2,000,000 copies.<ref name=\"United States certification\" /> In the United Kingdom, it peaked at number 49 in May 1974, and was certified Silver for shifting 60,000 physical copies.<ref name=\"United Kingdom certification\" />\n\nOn Canada's Top Albums/CDs chart conducted by ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'', the record debuted at number 76 during the week of February 23, 1974.<ref name=\"Canada debut\">{{cite web|title=Top RPM Albums: Issue 4984b|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4984b&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4984b.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4984b|publisher=RPM. Library and Archives Canada|accessdate=January 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118115811/http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4984b&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4984b.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4984b|archivedate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> ''The Way We Were'' peaked at number three on March 30 and spent another week at that same position on April 6.<ref name=\"Canada peak 1\">{{cite web|title=Top RPM Albums: Issue 4997a|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4997a&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4997a.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4997a|publisher=RPM. Library and Archives Canada|accessdate=January 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118115838/http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4997a&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4997a.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4997a|archivedate=January 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Canada peak 2\">{{cite web|title=Top RPM Albums: Issue 4999a|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4999a&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4999a.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4999a|publisher=RPM. Library and Archives Canada|accessdate=January 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118115129/http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4999a&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4999a.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4999a|archivedate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> It dropped to number nine the succeeding week and spent a total of twenty-three weeks in that country, with its final position being number 91 during the week of August 3.<ref name=\"Canada last position\">{{cite web|title=Top RPM Albums: Issue 5078b|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.5078b&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.5078b.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.5078b|publisher=RPM. Library and Archives Canada|accessdate=January 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118121130/http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.5078b&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.5078b.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.5078b|archivedate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> [[Music Canada]] reported in 1978 that the record had sold over 100,000 copies in their country, prompting it to become certified Platinum.<ref name=\"Canada certification\" /> In Australia and Japan, ''The Way We Were'' peaked at positions 7 and 73, respectively.<ref name=\"Australia\" /><ref name=\"Oricon\" /> It was later certified gold in the former country after selling approximately 35,000 copies.<ref name=\"Australia certification\" />\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| headline       = ''The Way We Were''{{spaced ndash}} {{nobold|Standard edition}}<ref name=\"The Way We Were liner notes\">{{cite AV media notes |title=The Way We Were |edition=CD release |others=Barbra Streisand |year=1974 |type=Liner notes |publisher=Columbia |id=C4K 44111}}</ref>\n| total_length       = 35:13\n| extra_column       = Producer(s)\n| title1         = Being at War with Each Other\n| writer1        = [[Carole King]]\n| length1        = 4:02\n| extra1        = [[Tommy LiPuma]]\n\n| title2         = [[Something So Right (song)|Something So Right]]\n| writer2        = [[Paul Simon]]\n| length2        = 4:26\n| extra2        = LiPuma\n\n| title3         = The Best Thing You've Ever Done\n| writer3        = [[Martin Charnin]]\n| length3        = 2:49\n| extra3        = [[Wally Gold]]\n\n| title4         = [[The Way We Were (song)|The Way We Were]]\n| writer4        = {{hlist|[[Alan and Marilyn Bergman|Alan Bergman]]|[[Alan and Marilyn Bergman|Marilyn Bergman]]|[[Marvin Hamlisch]]}}\n| length4        = 3:31\n| extra4        = [[Marty Paich]]\n\n| title5         = [[All in Love Is Fair#Barbra Streisand version|All in Love Is Fair]]\n| writer5        = [[Stevie Wonder]]\n| length5        = 3:50\n| extra5        = LiPuma\n\n| title6         = [[What Are You Doing the Rest of Your Life?]]\n| writer6        = {{hlist|A. Bergman|M. Bergman|[[Michel Legrand]]}}\n| length6        = 3:20\n| extra6        = Gold\n\n| title7         = Summer Me, Winter Me\n| writer7        = {{hlist|A. Bergman|Legrand}}\n| length7        = 2:55\n| extra7        = Gold\n\n| title8         = Pieces of Dreams\n| writer8        = {{hlist|A. Bergman|M. Bergman|Legrand}}\n| length8        = 3:27\n| extra8        = Gold\n\n| title9         = I've Never Been a Woman Before\n| writer9        = {{hlist|Tom Baird|[[Ron Miller (songwriter)|Ron Miller]]}}\n| length9        = 2:45\n| extra9        = Gold\n\n| title10         = [[My Buddy (song)|My Buddy]] / [[How About Me?|How About Me]]\n| writer10        = {{hlist|[[Gus Kahn]]|[[Walter Donaldson]]|[[Irving Berlin]]}}\n| length10        = 4:08\n| extra10        = Gold\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = ''Featuring the Hit Single The Way We Were and All in Love Is Fair''{{spaced ndash}} {{nobold|8-track cartridge edition}}<ref name=\"The Way We Were 2 liner notes\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Featuring the Hit Single The Way We Were and All in Love Is Fair | edition=8-track cartridge |others=Barbra Streisand |year=1974 |type=Liner notes |publisher=Columbia |id=PCA 32801}}</ref>\n| total_length = 35:21\n\n| title1         = Being at War with Each Other\n| length1        = 4:02\n\n| title2         = The Best Thing You've Ever Done\n| length2        = 2:49\n\n| title3         = Something So Right \n| note3         = Part 1\n| length3        = 2:44\n\n| title4         = Something So Right \n| note4         = Conclusion\n| length4        = 1:45\n\n| title5         = The Way We Were\n| length5        = 3:31\n\n| title6         = I've Never Been a Woman Before\n| length6        = 2:45\n\n| title7         = All in Love Is Fair\n| length7        = 3:50\n\n| title8         = What Are You Doing the Rest of Your Life?\n| length8        = 3:20\n\n| title9         = Summer Me, Winter Me\n| note9         = Part 1\n| length9        = 1:53\n\n| title10         = Summer Me, Winter Me\n| note10         = Conclusion\n| length10        = 1:07\n\n| title11         = Pieces of Dreams\n| length11        = 3:27\n\n| title12         = My Buddy / How About Me\n| length12        = 4:08\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of the CD edition of ''The Way We Were''.<ref name=\"The Way We Were liner notes\" />\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* Barbra Streisand{{spaced ndash}} vocals\n* [[David Bailey]]{{spaced ndash}} back cover photography\n* Nick DeCaro{{spaced ndash}} arranging {{small|(tracks 1, 2, 5)}}\n* Wally Gold{{spaced ndash}} production {{small|(tracks 3, 6\u201310)}}\n* [[Tommy LiPuma]]{{spaced ndash}} executive production, remixing\n* Stephen Marcussen{{spaced ndash}} remastering {{small|(CD and digital formats only)}}\n* [[Peter Matz]]{{spaced ndash}} arranging {{small|(tracks 6, 10)}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Claus Ogerman]]{{spaced ndash}} arranging {{small|(tracks 8, 9)}}\n* [[Marty Paich]]{{spaced ndash}} production, arranging {{small|(track 4)}}\n* Doug Sax{{spaced ndash}} original mastering\n* Steve Schapiro{{spaced ndash}} cover photography\n* [[Al Schmitt]]{{spaced ndash}} engineering, mixing\n* Stewart Whitmore{{spaced ndash}} digital editing {{small|(CD and digital formats only)}}\n{{col-end}}\n+(Frank DeCaro)(spaced ndash) music contractor\n\n== Charts ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n=== Weekly charts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1974)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br /> position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia Albums (''[[Go-Set]]'')<ref name=\"Australia\">{{cite web|title=Australian Albums: 15 June 1974|url=http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1974/19740615.html#albums|work=[[Go-Set]]|accessdate=January 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326150039/http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1974/19740615.html#albums|archivedate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n| 7\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia Albums ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref name=\"kent\">{{cite book|title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992]]|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book, St Ives, N.S.W |year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| 10\n|-\n{{albumchart|Canada|3|chartid=3399|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 15, 2017|refname=\"Canada\"}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Japanese Albums ([[Oricon]])<ref name=\"Oricon\">{{harvnb|Okamoto|2006|p=349}}</ref>\n|73\n|-\n{{albumchart|UK|49|artist=Barbra Streisand|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 15, 2017|refname=\"United Kingdom\"}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|1|artist=Barbra Streisand|rowheader=true|accessdate=January 15, 2017|refname=\"United States\"}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n=== Year-en