{"title_page": "Jerry Sullivan", "text_new": "{{for|the American judge|Jerry Bartholomew Sullivan}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n| name          = Jerry Sullivan\n| image         =Jerry Sullivan in 2009.jpg\n|caption = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1944|7|13|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Miami|Miami, Florida]]\n| current_team   = Arizona Cardinals\n| position = Offensive assistant\n| college  = [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]]\n| pastcoaching = \n*[[Kansas State Wildcats football|Kansas State]] (1971\u20131972)<br>Wide Receivers\n*[[Texas Tech Red Raiders football|Texas Tech]] (1973\u20131975) <br>Wide Receivers\n*[[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]] (1976\u20131982) <br>Wide Receivers\n*[[Indiana Hoosiers football|Indiana]] (Assistant) (1983)\n*[[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] (1984\u20131990) <br>Wide Receivers\n*[[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] (1991) <br>Wide Receivers\n*[[San Diego Chargers]]  ({{nfly|1992}}\u2013{{nfly|1996}}) <br>Wide Receivers\n*[[Detroit Lions]] ({{nfly|1997}}\u2013{{nfly|2000}})<br>Wide Receivers\n*[[Arizona Cardinals]] ({{nfly|2001}}\u2013{{nfly|2002}}) <br>Wide Receivers\n*Arizona Cardinals ({{nfly|2003}})<br>Offensive Coordinator \n*[[Miami Dolphins]] ({{nfly|2004}}) <br>Wide Receivers\n*[[San Francisco 49ers]] ({{nfly|2005}}\u2013{{nfly|2010}}) <br>Wide Receivers\n*[[Jacksonville Jaguars]] ({{nfly|2012}}\u2013{{nfly|2016}}) <br>Wide Receivers\n*LSU (2017)<br> Consultant \n*LSU (2018)<br> Pass Game Coordinator/Senior Offensive Assistant \n*Arizona Cardinals({{nfly|2019}}\u2013present)<br> Offensive Assistant \n}}\n\n'''Jerry Sullivan''' (born July 13, 1944) is an [[American football]] coach who is an offensive assistant for the [[Arizona Cardinals]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cardswire.usatoday.com/2019/08/12/report-jerry-sullivan-to-remain-on-cardinals-coaching-staff-through-season/ | title=Report: Jerry Sullivan to remain on Cardinals coaching staff through season |website=cardswire.usatoday.com | author=Root, Jess | date=August 12, 2019 | accessdate=August 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcardinals.com/team/coaches-roster/jerry-sullivan | title=Report: Jerry Sullivan Cardinals Bio |website=azcardinals.com | accessdate=August 27, 2019}}</ref>. He's spent 25-years in the [[National Football League]], 24 of them as a [[wide receivers]] coach.<ref name=\"SportNews\">{{cite news|last1=Clements|first1=Ron|title=A longtime NFL receivers coach explains what teams want to see at the NFL Combine|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nfl/news/longtime-nfl-receivers-coach-explains-what-teams-want-to-see-at-nfl-combine/q86e696uai4n1fv9xgn92i0yr|accessdate=23 April 2017|publisher=The Sporting News|date=28 February 2017}}</ref> He also spent over 20-years as a college football coach.\n\n==Collegiate coaching career== \nHis first coaching job was with Kansas state in 1971.<ref name=\"SportNews\"/> From 1973 to 1974, Sullivan was an assistant coach with the [[Texas Tech Red Raiders football|Texas Tech Red Raiders]] under head coach [[Jim Carlen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/text/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2010FBmediasupplement.pdf |title=2010 Texas Tech Red Raiders Football Media Guide |publisher=[[Texas Tech University]] |page=68 |location=[[Lubbock, Texas]] |accessdate=2011-07-06}}</ref> Sullivan then became wide receivers coach at [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]] from 1976 to 1982. In 1983, he spent a one-season as the [[Indiana Hoosiers football|Indiana Hoosiers]] wide receivers coach. From 1984 to 1990, Sullivan moved to [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] as the wide receivers coach<ref name=\"LSU84-90/Consultant\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nola.com/lsu/index.ssf/2017/08/veteran_nfl_and_college_receiv.html|title=Veteran NFL and college receivers coach Jerry Sullivan hired as an LSU consultant|publisher=nola.com|accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref> and he was also the wide receivers coach at [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] in 1991.\n\nIn 2017, Sullivan returned to the college ranks as a football consultant at LSU primarily focusing on wide receivers.<ref name=\"LSU84-90/Consultant\"/> On January 11, 2018, he moved to a full-time role on the coaching staff as senior offensive assistant/passing game coordinator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_dbba2140-f70e-11e7-a4cf-5f9270bc89e8.html|title='Age doesn't factor in': A close look at LSU football's rebuilt staff with addition of Jerry Sullivan|publisher=theadvocate.com|accessdate=2018-01-11}}</ref> On January 9, 2019, Sullivan announced his retirement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_c84821ca-1481-11e9-8a97-2f8b7cca68c8.html|title=Jerry Sullivan, LSU passing game coordinator, retires from football|publisher=the advocate.com|accessdate=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional coaching career==\nIn 1992, Sullivan moved to the professional coaching ranks with the NFL [[San Diego Chargers]]. He remained Chargers wide receivers coach until 1996. He then became the [[Detroit Lions]] wide receivers coach from 1997 to 2000. Starting in 2001, he was wide receivers coach with the [[Arizona Cardinals]] for two-seasons before being promoted to [[offensive coordinator]] for the [[2003 NFL Season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/crd/2003.htm|title=2003 Arizona Cardinals Statistics & Players|publisher=pro-football-reference.com|accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref> Sullivan then became the [[Miami Dolphins]] wide receivers coach in 2004 and from 2005 to 2010 he was the [[San Francisco 49ers]] wide receivers coach. From 2012 to 2016, he was the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] wide receivers coach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/coaches/SullJe0.htm|title=Jerry Sullivan|publisher=pro-football-reference.com|accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sullivan, Jerry}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals coaches]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions coaches]]\n[[Category:Florida State Seminoles football players]]\n[[Category:Indiana Hoosiers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Jaguars coaches]]\n[[Category:Kansas State Wildcats football coaches]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Miami Dolphins coaches]]\n[[Category:National Football League offensive coordinators]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes football coaches]]\n[[Category:San Diego Chargers coaches]]\n[[Category:San Francisco 49ers coaches]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Gamecocks football coaches]]\n[[Category:Texas Tech Red Raiders football coaches]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Miami]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the American judge|Jerry Bartholomew Sullivan}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n| name          = Jerry Sullivan\n| image         =Jerry Sullivan in 2009.jpg\n|caption = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1944|7|13|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Miami|Miami, Florida]]\n| current_team   = Arizona Cardinals\n| position = Offensive assistant\n| college  = [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]]\n| pastcoaching = \n*[[Kansas State Wildcats football|Kansas State]] (1971\u20131972)<br>Wide Receivers\n*[[Texas Tech Red Raiders football|Texas Tech]] (1973\u20131975) <br>Wide Receivers\n*[[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]] (1976\u20131982) <br>Wide Receivers\n*[[Indiana Hoosiers football|Indiana]] (Assistant) (1983)\n*[[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] (1984\u20131990) <br>Wide Receivers\n*[[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] (1991) <br>Wide Receivers\n*[[San Diego Chargers]]  ({{nfly|1992}}\u2013{{nfly|1996}}) <br>Wide Receivers\n*[[Detroit Lions]] ({{nfly|1997}}\u2013{{nfly|2000}})<br>Wide Receivers\n*[[Arizona Cardinals]] ({{nfly|2001}}\u2013{{nfly|2002}}) <br>Wide Receivers\n*Arizona Cardinals ({{nfly|2003}})<br>Offensive Coordinator \n*[[Miami Dolphins]] ({{nfly|2004}}) <br>Wide Receivers\n*[[San Francisco 49ers]] ({{nfly|2005}}\u2013{{nfly|2010}}) <br>Wide Receivers\n*[[Jacksonville Jaguars]] ({{nfly|2012}}\u2013{{nfly|2016}}) <br>Wide Receivers\n*LSU (2017)<br> Consultant \n*LSU (2018)<br> Pass Game Coordinator/Senior Offensive Assistant \n*Arizona Cardinals({{nfly|2019}}\u2013present)<br> Offensive Assistant \n}}\n\n'''Jerry Sullivan''' (born July 13, 1944) is an [[American football|football]] [[Coach (sport)|coach]] who is an Offensive Assistant for the [[Arizona Cardinals]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cardswire.usatoday.com/2019/08/12/report-jerry-sullivan-to-remain-on-cardinals-coaching-staff-through-season/ | title=Report: Jerry Sullivan to remain on Cardinals coaching staff through season |website=cardswire.usatoday.com | author=Root, Jess | date=August 12, 2019 | accessdate=August 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcardinals.com/team/coaches-roster/jerry-sullivan | title=Report: Jerry Sullivan Cardinals Bio |website=azcardinals.com | accessdate=August 27, 2019}}</ref>. He's spent 25-years in the [[National Football League]], 24 of them as a [[wide receivers]] coach.<ref name=\"SportNews\">{{cite news|last1=Clements|first1=Ron|title=A longtime NFL receivers coach explains what teams want to see at the NFL Combine|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nfl/news/longtime-nfl-receivers-coach-explains-what-teams-want-to-see-at-nfl-combine/q86e696uai4n1fv9xgn92i0yr|accessdate=23 April 2017|publisher=The Sporting News|date=28 February 2017}}</ref> He also spent over 20-years as a college football coach.\n\n==Collegiate coaching career== \nHis first coaching job was with Kansas state in 1971.<ref name=\"SportNews\"/> From 1973 to 1974, Sullivan was an assistant coach with the [[Texas Tech Red Raiders football|Texas Tech Red Raiders]] under head coach [[Jim Carlen]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/text/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2010FBmediasupplement.pdf |title=2010 Texas Tech Red Raiders Football Media Guide |publisher=[[Texas Tech University]] |page=68 |location=[[Lubbock, Texas]] |accessdate=2011-07-06}}</ref> Sullivan then became wide receivers coach at [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]] from 1976 to 1982. In 1983, he spent a one-season as the [[Indiana Hoosiers football|Indiana Hoosiers]] wide receivers coach. From 1984 to 1990, Sullivan moved to [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] as the wide receivers coach<ref name=\"LSU84-90/Consultant\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nola.com/lsu/index.ssf/2017/08/veteran_nfl_and_college_receiv.html|title=Veteran NFL and college receivers coach Jerry Sullivan hired as an LSU consultant|publisher=nola.com|accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref> and he was also the wide receivers coach at [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] in 1991.\n\nIn 2017, Sullivan returned to the college ranks as a football consultant at LSU primarily focusing on wide receivers.<ref name=\"LSU84-90/Consultant\"/> On January 11, 2018, he moved to a full-time role on the coaching staff as senior offensive assistant/passing game coordinator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_dbba2140-f70e-11e7-a4cf-5f9270bc89e8.html|title='Age doesn't factor in': A close look at LSU football's rebuilt staff with addition of Jerry Sullivan|publisher=theadvocate.com|accessdate=2018-01-11}}</ref> On January 9, 2019, Sullivan announced his retirement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theadvocate.com/baton_rouge/sports/lsu/article_c84821ca-1481-11e9-8a97-2f8b7cca68c8.html|title=Jerry Sullivan, LSU passing game coordinator, retires from football|publisher=the advocate.com|accessdate=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional coaching career==\nIn 1992, Sullivan moved to the professional coaching ranks with the NFL [[San Diego Chargers]]. He remained Chargers wide receivers coach until 1996. He then became the [[Detroit Lions]] wide receivers coach from 1997 to 2000. Starting in 2001, he was wide receivers coach with the [[Arizona Cardinals]] for two-seasons before being promoted to [[offensive coordinator]] for the [[2003 NFL Season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/crd/2003.htm|title=2003 Arizona Cardinals Statistics & Players|publisher=pro-football-reference.com|accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref> Sullivan then became the [[Miami Dolphins]] wide receivers coach in 2004 and from 2005 to 2010 he was the [[San Francisco 49ers]] wide receivers coach. From 2012 to 2016, he was the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] wide receivers coach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/coaches/SullJe0.htm|title=Jerry Sullivan|publisher=pro-football-reference.com|accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sullivan, Jerry}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals coaches]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions coaches]]\n[[Category:Florida State Seminoles football players]]\n[[Category:Indiana Hoosiers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Jaguars coaches]]\n[[Category:Kansas State Wildcats football coaches]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Miami Dolphins coaches]]\n[[Category:National Football League offensive coordinators]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes football coaches]]\n[[Category:San Diego Chargers coaches]]\n[[Category:San Francisco 49ers coaches]]\n[[Category:South Carolina Gamecocks football coaches]]\n[[Category:Texas Tech Red Raiders football coaches]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Miami]]\n", "name_user": "Jweiss11", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce in lead", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jerry_Sullivan"}
{"title_page": "Friedrich Haug", "text_new": "[[File:Johann Christoph Friedrich Haug.jpg|thumb|Johann Christoph Friedrich Haug]]\n[[File:Hauggrab.JPG|thumb|upright|Haug's grave in the Stuttgart Hoppenlau cemetery]]\n\n'''Friedrich Haug''' (Johann Christoph Friedrich Haug, born March 9, 1761 in [[Niederstotzingen]], \u2020 January 30, 1829 in [[Stuttgart]]) was a German official and poet.<ref>{{cite web|title=Johann Christoph Friedrich Haug (1761-1829) - Liebesgedichte |url=http://www.deutsche-liebeslyrik.de/haug_johann_christoph_friedrich.htm |website=Deutsche Liebeslyrik}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\nHaug is renowned particularly through his large number of [[epigram]]s, which he initially published under the name \"Hophthalmos\" (Sinngedichte, Frankfurt 1791; Epigrrams and Mixed Poems, Berlin 1805). From 1811 to 1817 he was the editor in charge of [[Johann Friedrich Cotta|Cotta]]'s ''[[Morgenblatt f\u00fcr gebildete St\u00e4nde|Morgenblatt]]''. With Friedrich Christoph Weisser, he published an epigramatic anthology (Stuttgart 1807\u20131809, 10 vols.). He also published fables, ballads, and stories.\n\nFriedrich  Haug was the son of Balthasar Haug, a teacher at the [[Karlsschule]]. In 1775, Haug attended this institute to study law. In 1784 he became secretary in the Ducal Secret Cabinet and court councillor and librarian in Stuttgart in 1817. Haug died on January 30, 1829.<ref>{{cite web|title=Haug, Johann Christoph Friedrich (Pseudonym F. Hophthalmos)|url=https://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz61070.html|website=deutsche-biographie}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.lieder.net/lieder/get_author_texts.html?AuthorId=1141 Compilation of texts]\n*[https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm?method=simpleSearch&query=118973649 Library portal]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haug, Friedrich}}\n[[Category:1761 births]]\n[[Category:1829 deaths]]\n[[Category:German male poets]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Johann Christoph Friedrich Haug.jpg|thumb|Johann Christoph Friedrich Haug]]\n[[File:Hauggrab.JPG|thumb|upright|Haug's grave in the Stuttgart Hoppenlau cemetery]]\n\n'''Friedrich Haug''' (Johann Christoph Friedrich Haug, born March 9, 1761 in [[Niederstotzingen]], \u2020 January 30, 1829 in [[Stuttgart]]) was a German official and poet.<ref>{{cite web|title=Johann Christoph Friedrich Haug (1761-1829) - Liebesgedichte |url=http://www.deutsche-liebeslyrik.de/haug_johann_christoph_friedrich.htm |website=Deutsche Liebeslyrik}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\nHaug is renowned particularly through his large number of [[epigram]]s, which he initially published under the name \"Hophthalmos\" (Sinngedichte, Frankfurt 1791; Epigrrams and Mixed Poems, Berlin 1805). From 1811 to 1817 he was the editor in charge of [[Johann Friedrich Cotta|Cotta]]'s ''[[Morgenblatt f\u00fcr gebildete St\u00e4nde|Morgenblatt]]''. With Friedrich Christoph Weisser, he published an epigramatic anthology (Stuttgart 1807\u20131809, 10 vols.). He also published fables, ballads, and stories.\n\nFriedrich  Haug was the son of Balthasar Haug, a teacher at the [[Karlsschule]]. In 1775, Haug attended this institute to study law. In 1784 he became secretary in the Ducal Secret Cabinet and court councillor and librarian in Stuttgart in 1817. Haug died on January 30, 1829.<ref>{{cite web|title=Haug, Johann Christoph Friedrich (Pseudonym F. Hophthalmos)|url=https://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz61070.html|website=deutsche-biographie}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.lieder.net/lieder/get_author_texts.html?AuthorId=1141 Compilation of texts]\n*[https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm?method=simpleSearch&query=118973649 Library portal]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haug, Friedrich}}\n[[Category:1761 births]]\n[[Category:1829 deaths]]\n[[Category:German male poets]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich_Haug"}
{"title_page": "Royal Dansk", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Vestfyns_Hjemstavnsgaard.jpg|thumb|The Hjemstavnsgaard farmhouse on the island of [[Funen]] in Denmark is shown on the container.]]\n'''Royal Dansk''' (meaning \"Royal Danish\") is a Danish brand of [[Butter cookie|butter cookies]]. It is known for its distinctive [[royal blue]] round [[tin box|tin container]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_asia/article/ned7az/the-enduring-appeal-of-royal-dansk-butter-cookies|title=The Enduring Appeal of Royal Dansk Butter Cookies|last=|first=|date=14 December 2017|website=|publisher=[[Vice (website)|Vice]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt was manufactured by the Danish company [[Kelsen (company)|Kelsen]]<ref name=\":0\" /> (a part of [[Campbell Soup Company|Campbell]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tgcom24.mediaset.it/economia/acquisizioni-ferrero-compra-i-biscotti-danesi-di-kelsen-group_3219889-201902a.shtml|title=Acquisizioni, Ferrero compra i biscotti danesi di Kelsen Group|last=|first=|date=|website=[[TgCom24]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> until the company was acquired by the Italian manufacturer [[Ferrero SpA|Ferrero]] in 2019 for $300 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/30/campbell-soup-shares-rise-after-beating-profit-estimates-on-cost-cuts.html|title=Campbell Soup shares rise after beating profit estimates on cost cuts|last=|first=|date=30 August 2019|website=[[CNBC]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foodbusinessnews.net/articles/14563-ferrero-affiliate-completes-kelsen-acquisition?v=preview|title=Ferrero affiliate completes Kelsen acquisition|last=|first=|date=|website=Food Business News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe blue tin box features an image of the Hjemstavnsgaard farmhouse on the island of [[Funen]] in Denmark.<ref name=\":0\" />\nThe container has become a part of [[popular culture]], with many people having kept the tin box and used it for storing other items, most commonly [[sewing]] supplies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/royal-dansk-cookie-tin-found-unusual|title=What's in Your Royal Dansk Cookie Tin?|last=Mejia|first=Paula|date=27 March 2018|website=[[Atlas Obscura]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://homes.nine.com.au/decor/biscuit-tin-sewing-supplies-royal-dansk/9446c43e-7cb8-433a-91e5-513a09418fd1|title=Reddit discovers the world's most popular repurposing hack|last=Taylor|first=Sonia|date=|website=[[Nine.com.au]]|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/royal-dansk-cookie-tins|title=Sewing Kits, Umbilical Cords, and Mold: Here\u2019s What You Keep in Royal Dansk Tins|last=Mejia|first=Paula|date=12 April 2018|website=[[Atlas Obscura]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.interaksyon.com/breaking-news/2018/06/01/127948/how-danish-butter-cookie-containers-became-sewing-kits/|title=How Danish butter cookie containers became sewing kits|last=Madarang|first=Catalina Ricci S.|date=1 June 2018|website=[[Interaksyon]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/codeswitch/2015/10/16/448898412/fess-up-grannies-you-ate-the-butter-cookies|title='Fess Up, Grannies, You Ate The Butter Cookies|last=|first=|date=|website=[[NPR]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Brand name cookies]]\n[[Category:Danish cakes]]\n[[Category:Food brands of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Ferrero brands]]\n\n\n{{Denmark-stub}}\n{{Food-company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:Vestfyns_Hjemstavnsgaard.jpg|thumb|The Hjemstavnsgaard farmhouse on the island of [[Funen]] in Denmark is shown on the container.]]\n'''Royal Dansk''' (meaning \"Royal Danish\") is a Danish brand of [[Butter cookie|butter cookies]]. It is known for its distinctive [[royal blue]] round [[tin box|tin container]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_asia/article/ned7az/the-enduring-appeal-of-royal-dansk-butter-cookies|title=The Enduring Appeal of Royal Dansk Butter Cookies|last=|first=|date=14 December 2017|website=|publisher=[[Vice (website)|Vice]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIt was manufactured by the Danish company [[Kelsen (company)|Kelsen]]<ref name=\":0\" /> (a part of [[Campbell Soup Company|Campbell]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tgcom24.mediaset.it/economia/acquisizioni-ferrero-compra-i-biscotti-danesi-di-kelsen-group_3219889-201902a.shtml|title=Acquisizioni, Ferrero compra i biscotti danesi di Kelsen Group|last=|first=|date=|website=[[TgCom24]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> until the company was acquired by the Italian manufacturer [[Ferrero SpA|Ferrero]] in 2019 for $300 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/30/campbell-soup-shares-rise-after-beating-profit-estimates-on-cost-cuts.html|title=Campbell Soup shares rise after beating profit estimates on cost cuts|last=|first=|date=30 August 2019|website=[[CNBC]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foodbusinessnews.net/articles/14563-ferrero-affiliate-completes-kelsen-acquisition?v=preview|title=Ferrero affiliate completes Kelsen acquisition|last=|first=|date=|website=Food Business News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 April 2020}}</